   "source": [
    "## 6. Three key insights"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8f85d464",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Insight 1 — Bill size is the strongest driver of tip amount.**\n",
    "`total_bill` and `tip` show a strong positive correlation (see heatmap value above). In dollar terms, bigger checks reliably produce bigger tips — this is the single most predictable relationship in the dataset, and it holds across both lunch and dinner service (see the scatter plot's color grouping)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "65c56be5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Insight 2 — Party size mainly explains bill size, not tipping generosity.**\n",
    "Larger parties order more food and rack up bigger bills (positive correlation between `size` and `total_bill`), but this is really a volume effect rather than individual generosity — it's consistent with Week 1's finding that average tip rises with party size mostly because the underlying bill is larger, not because bigger groups tip a higher percentage."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a6b61749",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Insight 3 — Saturday has the most visits but the lowest average tip percentage (~15%), while Friday tips the highest (~17%).**\n",
    "Even though Week 1 showed Saturday and Sunday have the most visits, Saturday customers actually tip the smallest share of their bill on average, and Friday (a lower-volume day) tips the most generously. This shows that *volume* of customers and *generosity* of customers are two separate patterns — a busy day isn't automatically the best-tipping day."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a9a544a7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Summary\n",
    "- Correlation analysis confirmed `total_bill` is the dominant driver of both `tip` and, indirectly, `size`.\n",
    "- The heatmap and scatter plots made the two strongest numeric relationships easy to spot and quantify.\n",
    "- Grouping by day surfaced a categorical pattern (tip % varies by day) that wasn't visible from the numeric correlations alone, showing why both approaches are needed for a full picture."
   ]
  }
